article.description: Jermaine O'Neal scored 21 points and Ron Mercer, playing his longest stint since returning from the injured list, added 17 as the Pacers defeated the Miami Heat 104-94 Friday night.
article.headline: Heat hurting playoff chances with home troubles
article.linkText: Pacers win game with playoff implications in Miami
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- The Indiana Pacers were more than happy to spoil another night at home for the Miami Heat. Jermaine O'Neal scored 21 points and Ron Mercer, playing his longest stint since returning from the injured list, added 17 as the Pacers defeated the Miami Heat 104-94 Friday night. Indiana remained tied with Charlotte for seventh place in the Eastern Conference, 3 1/2 games ahead of Miami. The Pacers have won five of their last six games and play host to the Hornets on Sunday. "We have to take the same attitude we had tonight with us the rest of the way," Pacers guard Reggie Miller said. "Tonight was a battle of wills, and we wanted to instill our will against them." The Heat lost for only the fourth time in their last 12 games but continued a disturbing trend. The Heat, who dropped their second straight home game, are one of only two teams with more victories on the road than at home. "We can't seem to take care of business at home, and that's disappointing," Heat forward Brian Grant said. "It's been our Achilles' heel coming down the stretch, and we have to find a way to get it done." The Heat have 15 games remaining, and 11 are against teams with winning records. "Every game has the same value," Miami center Alonzo Mourning said. "We must keep winning. It's tough to wipe them away, especially in the stretch run. We have to get our thing together to make something happen." Miller scored 20 points for the Pacers, including a 3-pointer late in the game that helped clinch it. Brad Miller scored 15 points and had eight rebounds. Mercer, playing only his fourth game since a Jan. 22 injury as a member of the Chicago Bulls, played a total of 19 minutes and scored 11 of his points in the fourth quarter. Mercer was returning to the same building where the knee injury took place in a Bulls' loss to the Heat. "I'm starting to feel more comfortable," said Mercer, who comes off the bench after starting in Chicago. "It's good to have fun. I know my role is a little different than it was in Chicago. That's fine with me -- just as long as we're winning. "I'm glad not to be on the bottom any more, and to be on a team and helping them get to the playoffs. I'm willing to sacrifice to do that." Mourning and Eddie Jones each scored 20 points, and Eddie House added 18 for Miami. Indiana's lead was down to six points, 93-87, when Reggie Miller hit his key 3-pointer to provide a 96-87 lead with 52 seconds left. The Pacers shot 65.6 percent in the first half in opening a 56-41 lead. "We got on a roll," Pacers coach Isiah Thomas said. "We got hot and the shots started pouring in. It seemed like every time we shot the ball, it went in." The Pacers never trailed, leading 26-18 after one period and stretching it to 17 just before halftime. For the Heat, who lost at home to Philadelphia on Tuesday but then won in the Sixers' building the following night, the deficit was too much to overcome. "They played better than we did at the beginning, pulled out and got a big lead, and we had to play catch-up the rest of the way," Mourning said.

Game notes
The Pacers drew four technical fouls. Brad Miller and Ron Artest each were assessed technical fouls in the first quarter -- Miller for arguing a call after being whistled for a foul against Mourning, and Artest for kicking the scorer's table during a timeout. Coach Isiah Thomas picked up a technical in the second quarter and Jamaal Tinsley in the third. ... Indiana beat Miami for the first time in three games this year and for only the fourth time in the last 11. ...Indiana is 9-6 since the Feb. 19 trade that sent Jalen Rose and Travis Best to the Bulls in return for Brad Miller, Ron Artest, Ron Mercer and Kevin Ollie. ... The Heat carry an 11-game winning streak on the second night of back-to-backs when they visit San Antonio on Saturday. ... The Heat and Hornets are the only teams in the NBA with more wins on the road than at home. The Heat are 17-18 on the road compared to 14-18 at home.
